When constructing a bridge with an effective width of 16.5 m (three lanes on each side in Road Standard Class 1 Class 1), if the conventional two-lane cross section on one side is converted to a three-lane cross section, the box girder will become larger and a two-chamber box. It has to be a digit [346]. As a result, the weight increases, the width of the lower floor board increases, and the piers and foundation structures that support it also increase in scale, increasing costs. Therefore, by incorporating the struts into the superstructure, the upper floor plate (overhanging floor plate) is supported instead of the box girder, and as a result, the cross section of the box girder is reduced and the weight of the main girder is reduced. This reduces the width of the lower floor and reduces the cost by reducing the piers and foundations. [347]
